         <abstract id="aspace_e8bd44895717297934c804fcddcbce11">The collection includes artwork and other materials created by Allan Rohan Crite. Included are Crite's sketchbooks and letterbooks, which Crite made by stapling together incoming and outgoing carbon copies of correspondence and ink sketches. Crite sometimes typed correspondence on stationery with his photocopied art. The letterbooks include both work related and personal correspondence, particularly between Crite and the churches he worked with. Visits to churches, art works commissioned for churches, and upcoming meetings are included in the topics discussed in the correspondence. Crite's class notes, church newsletters, and two illustrated liturgical drama typescripts are also included.</abstract>
      </did>
      <bioghist id="aspace_3c2ba3353a15fdada0051591b7a161ff">
         <head>Biographical / Historical</head>
         <p>Allan Rohan Crite was an artist, writer, and librarian. He was born in Plainfield, New Jersey on March 20, 1910. Crite attended the School of the Museum of Fine Arts in Boston and graduated in 1936. Crite worked with the Works Progress Administration followed by a position as a draughtsman at the Boston Naval Yard from 1940 to 1974. Working in a variety of media including watercolors, drawings, lithographs, and oil paintings, Crite often depicted scenes of everyday African American life. Throughout the Depression and into the 1940s, Crite painted a series of neighborhood paintings focused on his Roxbury neighborhood. Crite also focused on religious themes in his art including illustrating church service programs for parishes and painting murals on churches.</p>
      </bioghist>
      <scopecontent id="aspace_81197e81da37ae0f91ffbffea0a9159c">
         <head>Scope and Contents</head>
         <p>The collection includes artwork and other materials created by Allan Rohan Crite. Included are Crite's sketchbooks and letterbooks, which Crite made by stapling together incoming and outgoing carbon copies of correspondence and ink sketches. Crite sometimes typed correspondence on stationery with his photocopied art. The letterbooks include both work related and personal correspondence, particularly between Crite and the churches he worked with. Visits to churches, art works commissioned for churches, and upcoming meetings are included in the topics discussed in the correspondence. Crite's class notes, church newsletters, and two illustrated liturgical drama typescripts are also included.</p>
      </scopecontent>
      <arrangement id="aspace_93d78703ed77433c48ac88ccd93ef793">
         <head>Arrangement</head>
         <p>The material is grouped by subject and format.</p>
      </arrangement>
      <acqinfo id="aspace_4c74c69ae8c09013ae6935c5f60f722f">
         <head>Immediate Source of Acquisition</head>
         <p>Purchased from James Cummins Bookseller on the Alfred Z. Baker Jr. Fund, 2021.</p>
      </acqinfo>
